85% of Nigerian women at one point in their lives wear a weave, wig or hair extension. A short survey carried out with an experimental sample of 40 women, shows 70% of them either had on a sew-in weave or a wig. With the huge sum, we spend on our weaves and wigs; it is of little wonder why weave essentials are an important topic. Here are ways you can take care of your weaves: <img class="aligncenter wp-image-769531 size-full lazyload" src="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/weave..-google.jpg" alt="" width="1000" height="1000" srcset="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/weave..-google.jpg 1000w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/weave..-google-598x598.jpg 598w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/weave..-google-100x100.jpg 100w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/weave..-google-200x200.jpg 200w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/weave..-google-487x487.jpg 487w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/weave..-google-974x974.jpg 974w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/weave..-google-240x240.jpg 240w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/weave..-google-480x480.jpg 480w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/weave..-google-600x600.jpg 600w" sizes="(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px" /> The first thing is to KNOW your weave. At the point of purchase, make sure you buy a wig that is wefted as this goes a long way in determining how much your weave will shred. This rule applies to both fibre weave and Human hair. <img class="aligncenter wp-image-769536 size-medium lazyload" src="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/detangling-your-hair-sorce-google-1062x598.jpg" alt="" width="1062" height="598" srcset="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/detangling-your-hair-sorce-google-1062x598.jpg 1062w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/detangling-your-hair-sorce-google-640x360.jpg 640w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/detangling-your-hai